<L>And which the ruling pa&s;&s;ion of your mind.</L></Q>
<P><HI>Stooping</HI> to Lyrick Lays, though not inapplicable to &s;ome of the lighter odes of Horace, is not de&s;crip|tive of the general character of the Lyrick Mu&s;e. <HI>Mu&s;a dedit Fidibus Divos, &amp;c.</HI></P>
<P>Pope takes up the &s;ame thought in his E&s;&s;ay on Critici&s;m.</P>
<Q><L>Be &s;ure your&s;elf and your own reach to know,</L>
<L>How far your genius, ta&s;te, and learning go;</L>
<L><PB N="47" REF="105">Launch not beyond your depth, but be di&s;creet,</L>
<L>And mark that point where &s;en&s;e and dulne&s;s meet.</L></Q>
